 1950s. Along the way, it examines and reassesses the egalitarian political thought of many significant figures in the history of the British Left, including L. T. Hobhouse, R. H. Tawney and Anthony Crosland. Newly available in paperback for the first time, this book demonstrates that the British Left has historically been distinguished from its ideological competitors on the Centre and the Right by a commitment to a demanding form of economic egalitarianism. It shows that this egalitarianism has come to be neglected or caricatured by politicians and scholars alike, and is more surprising and sophisticated than is often imagined. Equality and the British Left offers a compelling new perspective on British political thought that will appeal to scholars and students of British history and political theory, and to anyone interested in contemporary debates about progressive politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEqualityzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiberalismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aRight and left (Political science). 0aSocialismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh  aBritish Left.  aL. T. Hobhouse.  aNew Left.  aearly twentieth century.  aeconomic egalitarianism.  aegalitarian society.  aequality.  aprogressive liberalism.  arevisionist social democracy.  asocialism.1 aJackson, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779219840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792198/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013